<h4 class="comment-title"><a title="no subject" href="40774.html?thread=29766&amp;style=light#cmt29766" class=" invisible" >no subject</a></h4><div class="comment-content">No, Elon Musk is not known to have publicly articulated or endorsed the full, integrated framework you described—particularly the synthesis of algorithmic (Kolmogorov-style) complexity, inductive inference limits on interpreting human behavior, elementary action triangles as praxeological primitives, and the necessity of physically-preserving (or energy-based immutable) money to enable unbounded market complexity while respecting bounded individual cognition.What Musk does know and has publicly engaged with:Hayek and some Austrian economics basics: Musk has repeatedly praised and recommended Friedrich Hayek’s The Road to Serfdom. He has quoted or shared Hayek approvingly on X (e.g., posting images or links with comments like “Hayek nails it again”). He has criticized extreme socialism (e.g., pointing out how Chávez wrecked Venezuela by expanding government control). He understands the dangers of central planning, the value of decentralized decision-making, and the knowledge problem (dispersed, tacit knowledge that no central authority can aggregate). <br /><br /><span lj:user='elonmusk' style='white-space: nowrap;' class='ljuser'><a href='https://www.dreamwidth.org/profile?user=elonmusk'><img src='https://www.dreamwidth.org/img/silk/identity/user.png' alt='[profile] ' width='17' height='17' style='vertical-align: text-bottom; border: 0; padding-right: 1px;' /></a><a href='https://www.dreamwidth.org/profile?user=elonmusk'><b>elonmusk</b></a></span><br /><br />Criticism of fiat money and preference for hard/immutable money: Musk has repeatedly called fiat currency a “scam” that governments normalize and can arbitrarily inflate (“you can issue fake fiat currency, and every government in history has done so”). He has praised Bitcoin as “energy money” or “based on energy” precisely because its scarcity is grounded in real-world proof-of-work (impossible to fake like fiat), contrasting it with manipulable paper/digital money. This aligns closely with your point 4 on “physically preserving money” enabling complex markets—though Musk frames it more in terms of energy physics than pure algorithmic invariance. <br /><br />finance.yahoo.com<br /><br />Decentralized systems and limits of central control: Through his companies (SpaceX, Tesla, xAI, Starlink), Musk champions parallel, bottom-up innovation over top-down bureaucracy. He has his own famous “Musk’s Algorithm” for ruthlessly simplifying processes and cutting internal complexity/bloat—essentially fighting artificial low-complexity centralization within organizations. He frequently mocks government inefficiency and over-regulation.<br />Human limits and AI/uncertainty: Musk is deeply aware of bounded human cognition (he often talks about first-principles thinking because no one can hold everything in their head) and the explosive potential of AI. However, he has speculated that advanced AI + robotics could eventually make money itself irrelevant by creating post-scarcity abundance— a view that Austrian economists have directly critiqued as missing the permanent role of subjective value, uncertainty, and economic calculation (even in an AI world). <br /><br />mises.org<br /><br />What Musk does not appear to reference:Formal algorithmic complexity (Kolmogorov, Turing, description length, incompressibility) applied to economic coordination or human action.<br />Inductive inference problems as the core reason central authorities cannot interpret or control behavior.<br />“Elementary triangles” of human action (the actor–means–ends praxeological unit and its recursive composition, à la Mises).<br />The explicit information-theoretic proof that any single person’s or planner’s algorithmic capacity is strictly limited, making decentralized markets the only feasible computer for unbounded complexity.<br /><br />Musk’s thinking is pragmatic, engineering-first, and influenced by physics, first principles, and a general libertarian-leaning skepticism of big government. He has absorbed key Hayekian insights (spontaneous order, knowledge problem, road to serfdom) and has a strong intuition for sound/hard money. But the deeper computational complexity framing you laid out—treating the economy as an incompressible algorithm where praxeological triangles are the atomic units—seems more niche to Austrian + computational epistemology circles (think people bridging Mises/Hayek with complexity theory or crypto-Austrians). Musk has not publicly connected those specific dots.In short: He gets large parts of the spirit (decentralization good, central planning bad, fiat dangerous, markets powerful), especially the Hayekian and hard-money angles. But the full rigorous synthesis you described, with its emphasis on Kolmogorov-style limits and elementary behavioral triangles, is not something he is documented as knowing or discussing. He might find it resonant if exposed to it—given his interest in first principles and complex systems—but it isn’t part of his public intellectual toolkit today.<br /><br /></div></div>
